06050nam a22008055i 9781782388609DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20052005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97817823886097 a10.1515/97817823886092doi  a(DE-B1597)636214  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aD16.9b.N36 2005 7aHIS0160002bisacsh04a907/.222200aNarration, Identity, and Historical Consciousness /ced. by Jürgen Straub. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMaking Sense of History ;v300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the Series -- tForeword -- tPart I THEORETICAL POSITIONS AND REFLECTIONS -- tCHAPTER 1 Narrative Psychology and Historical Consciousness Relationships and Perspectives -- tCHAPTER 2 Past and Present as Narrative Constructions -- tCHAPTER 3 Telling Stories, Making History Toward a Narrative Psychology of the Historical Construction of Meaning -- tCHAPTER 4 Narrative, Moral Identity, and Historical Consciousness: A Social Constructionist Account -- tCHAPTER 5 Narrative Truth and Identity Formation: Abduction and Abuse Stories as Metaphors -- tPart 2 ON THE DEVELOPMENT OF NARRATIVE COMPETENCE AND HISTORICAL CONSCIOUSNESS -- tCHAPTER 6 The Concept of Time and the Faculty of Judgment in the Ontogenesis of Historical Consciousness -- tCHAPTER 7 Historical Consciousness: The Progress of Knowledge in a Postprogressive Age -- tPart 3 EMPIRICAL RESEARCH/ CASE STUDIES -- tCHAPTER 8 Empirical Psychological Approaches to the Historical Consciousness of Children -- tCHAPTER 9 The Psychological Study of Historical Consciousness -- tCHAPTER 10 Biography—A Dream? Self-Chronicling in the Age of Psychoanalysis -- tCHAPTER 11 Authenticity and Authority On Understanding the Shoah -- tCHAPTER 12 Albert Speer’s Memories of the Future On the Historical Consciousness of a Leading Figure in the Third Reich -- tBibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA generally acknowledged characteristic of modern life, namely the temporalization of experience, inextricable from our intensified experience of contingency and difference, has until now remained largely outside psychology’s purview. Wherever questions about the development, structure, and function of the concept of time have been posed – for example by Piaget and other founders of genetic structuralism – they have been concerned predominantly with concepts of "physical", chronometrical time, and related concepts (e.g., "velocity"). All the contributions to the present volume attempt to close this gap. A larger number are especially interested in the narration of stories. Overviews of the relevant literature, as well as empirical case studies, appear alongside theoretical and methodological reflections. Most contributions refer to specifically historical phenomena and meaning-constructions. Some touch on the subjects of biographical memory and biographical constructions of reality. Of all the various affinities between the contributions collected here, the most important is their consistent attention to issues of the constitution and representation of temporal experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aConsciousness. 0aHistoriography. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh1 aBillmann-Mahecha, Elfriede, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoothe, Brigitte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrumlik, Micha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruner, Jerome S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb